'''Jarell Amorin Quansah''' (born 29 January 2003) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{German football updater|BaLeverk}} club [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

== Youth career ==
Quansah joined [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] at the age of five, from Woolston Rovers and Rope and Anchor FC in his native [[Warrington]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal |last=Jack Heale |date=25 May 2021 |title=The next footballing talent to come out of Warrington on Liverpool's books? |url=https://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/sport/19327641.liverpool-fc-englands-youth-talent-jarell-quansah/ |url-status=live |journal=[[Warrington Guardian]] |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230602203202/https://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/sport/19327641.liverpool-fc-englands-youth-talent-jarell-quansah/ |archive-date=2 June 2023 |access-date=30 June 2022}}</ref><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=O'Neill |first=Caoimhe |date=13 May 2021 |title=FA Youth Cup: Jarell Quansah emerges as a leader during Liverpool's semi-final victory |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/2585383/2021/05/13/fa-youth-cup-jarell-quansah-emerges-as-a-leader-during-liverpools-semi-final-victory/ |url-access=registration |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=[[The Athletic]] |language=en |quote=Quansah, an England Under-18s international who is also eligible to represent Ghana and Barbados, showed incredible speed to recover the ball}}</ref><ref name=":5" />

== Club career ==
=== Liverpool ===
Quansah signed his first contract with the Premier League club on 4 February 2021.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Mathieu Rault |date=4 February 2021 |title=Liverpool : premier contrat pro pour le jeune défenseur Jarell Quansah |url=https://www.footmercato.net/a3467376275581311259-liverpool-premier-contrat-pro-pour-le-jeune-defenseur-jarell-quansah |access-date=30 June 2022 |website={{ill|Foot Mercato|fr}} |language=fr}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web |date=4 February 2021 |title=Jarell Quansah signs first professional contract with LFC |url=https://legacy.liverpoolfc.com/news/academy/424796-jarell-quansah-signs-first-professional-contract-with-lfc  |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=[[Liverpool Football Club|Liverpool FC]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=29 March 2021 |title=Highly-rated Ghanaian centre-back Jarell Quansah buzzing after penning first professional contract at Liverpool |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/highly-rated-ghanaian-centre-back-jarell-quansah-buzzing-after-penning-first-professional-contract-at-liverpool |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=GhanaSoccernet}}</ref> During this [[2020–21 Liverpool F.C. season|2020–21 season]], he captained the Liverpool [[Professional Development League|under-18 side]] that made it to the [[FA Youth Cup]] final, along the likes of [[Billy Koumetio]], [[Melkamu Frauendorf]], [[Max Woltman]], [[Conor Bradley]] and [[Luke Chambers (footballer, born 2004)|Luke Chambers]].<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite journal|last=Rimmer |first=Joe |date=19 December 2021 |title=Jarell Quansah is Liverpool's 'man-mountain' teen included in squad for Spurs |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jarell-quansah-liverpool-tottenham-breaking-22512301 |journal=[[Liverpool Echo]]  |access-date=30 June 2022}}</ref>

The [[2021–22 Liverpool F.C. season|next season]], Quansah captained the [[2021–22 UEFA Youth League|UEFA Youth League]] team,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rousingthekop.com/2021/11/03/liverpool-u19s-beat-atletico-madrid-2-0-thanks-to-smart-max-woltman-finish/|website=Rousing The Kop|publisher=[[NewsNow]]|accessdate=30 June 2022|title=Liverpool U19s beat Atletico Madrid 2–0 thanks to smart Max Woltman finish|first=Alex|last=Caple|date=3 November 2021}}</ref> whilst also playing in the [[Professional Development League|Premier League 2]] with the reserves, and playing a key role with the latter during the [[Lancashire Senior Cup]] victory.<ref name=":6">{{Cite journal |last=Doyle |first=Ian |date=11 April 2022 |title=Liverpool seal place in another final as midfielder sends first-team reminder |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-final-midfielder-first-team-23659844 |journal=[[Liverpool Echo]] |access-date=30 June 2022}}</ref><ref name=":7">{{Cite journal |last1=Squires |first1=Theo |last2=Pinnock |first2=Hannah |date=4 May 2022 |title=Burnley U23s vs Liverpool U23s -Norris hero as Reds win Lancashire Senior Cup |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-burnley-cup-final-live-23865169 |journal=Liverpool Echo |access-date=30 June 2022}}</ref>

Quansah then made his first appearance on the team sheet with the senior team, in the [[2021–22 Premier League|Premier League]] and [[EFL Cup]],<ref name=":4"/><ref name=":3">{{Cite web|last=Kumar |first=Vineet |date=28 December 2021 |title=Jarell Quansah – the Liverpool teenager who made the bench against Spurs |url=https://premierleaguenewsnow.com/jarell-quansah-liverpool-teenager-made-bench-vs-spurs/  |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=Premier League News Now}}</ref> not coming off the bench however as Liverpool won both domestic cups, finishing just two victories short from a historic quadruple.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bevan |first=Chris |date=2 May 2022 |title=How Liverpool's quadruple bid has made English history |work=[[BBC Sport]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61292082 |access-date=8 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/30965/12579011/liverpools-quadruple-quest-how-do-jurgen-klopps-side-fare-in-historic-bid|title=Liverpool's Quadruple quest: How do Jurgen Klopp's side fare in historic bid?|first=Richard|last=Morgan|website=Sky Sports|date=19 May 2022|access-date=8 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12623493/liverpool-beaten-by-real-madrid-in-champions-league-final-and-left-with-two-cups-so-has-this-season-been-a-success|title=Liverpool beaten by Real Madrid in Champions League final and left with two cups - so has this season been a success?|first=Adam|last=Bate|website=Sky Sports|date=29 May 2022|access-date=8 July 2022}}</ref>

On 20 January 2023, Quansah joined [[EFL League One|League One]] club [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolrovers.co.uk/news/2023/january/quansah-signs/|title=Jarell Quansah joins Rovers on loan|website=www.bristolrovers.co.uk|date=20 January 2023|accessdate=20 January 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64348562|publisher=BBC Sport|title=Bristol Rovers sign Liverpool's Quansah on loan|date=20 January 2023|access-date=21 January 2023}}</ref> He made his senior debut on 28 January, playing the duration of a 5–1 defeat to [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]], impressing despite the result.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64356481|title=Morecambe 5–1 Bristol Rovers: Joey Barton calls performance 'rude awakening'|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 January 2023|accessdate=29 January 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/bristol-rovers-verdict-bartons-big-8086165|title=Bristol Rovers verdict: Barton's big call, class between the chaos and the man Gas miss the most|publisher=Bristol Post|last1=Frost|first1=Sam|date=29 January 2023|accessdate=29 January 2023}}</ref> Following an impressive performance in a 0–0 draw with [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]], Rovers' manager [[Joey Barton]] predicted Quansah to be destined for the top level of the game, citing his ability on the ball as a key asset.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bristolpost.co.uk/sport/football/barton-bristol-liverpool-jarell-quansah-8150998|title=Joey Barton predicts big things for Liverpool's Jarell Quansah as he stars for Bristol Rovers|publisher=Bristol Post|last1=Piercy|first1=James|date=15 February 2023|accessdate=15 February 2023}}</ref> On 18 March, he received a first career sending-off for violent conduct in the last minutes of a 2–0 home defeat to [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64923433|title=Bristol Rovers 0–2 Portsmouth|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2023|accessdate=19 March 2023}}</ref>

On 27 August 2023, Quansah made his professional debut for Liverpool, coming on as a substitute for [[Joël Matip]] in a 2–1 win over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the [[2023–24 Premier League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Darwin Nunez's late double sees 10-man Liverpool beat Newcastle at St. James' Park |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/darwin-nunezs-late-double-sees-10-man-liverpool-beat-newcastle-st-james-park |website=Liverpool FC |date=August 2023 |access-date=27 August 2023}}</ref>  On 14 December, Quansah scored his first goal for Liverpool against [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Union Saint-Gilloise]] in the [[2023–24 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa league]] in a 2–1 defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/dec/14/union-saint-gilloise-liverpool-europa-league-match-report|website=The Guardian|accessdate=15 December 2023|title=Liverpool's youngsters fall short and fail to ruin Union Saint-Gilloise party|first=Andy|last=Hunter|date=14 December 2023}}</ref>

On 25 February 2024, Liverpool played in the [[2024 EFL Cup final]] against Chelsea at [[Wembley Stadium]]. During extra time, in the 106th minute of the game, Quansah was substituted on for [[Ibrahima Konaté]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Matchdetails from Chelsea - Liverpool played on Sunday 25 February 2024 - LFChistory - Stats galore for Liverpool FC! |url=https://www.lfchistory.net/SeasonArchive/Game/5986 |access-date=2024-03-03 |website=www.lfchistory.net}}</ref> Liverpool went on to win the match 1–0 after extra time, earning Quansah his first trophy with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68397980|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=3 March 2024|title=Carabao Cup: 'Jurgen Klopp's kids beat Chelsea's billion-pound bottle-jobs' - pundits react to Liverpool triumph|first=Michael|last=Beardmore|date=25 February 2024}}</ref> Later that year, on 13 May, he scored his first Premier League goal in a 3–3 away draw against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/premier-league/2023-2024/aston-villa-v-liverpool-premier-league-live_sto10143667/story.shtml|website=Eurosport|accessdate=13 May 2024|title=Aston Villa 3–3 Liverpool: Hosts close on Champions League after late Jhon Duran double denies Reds|first=Paul|last=Hassall|date=13 May 2024}}</ref> and then scored for a second successive game against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in [[Jürgen Klopp]]'s last game in charge of the club on 19 May 2024. On 7 October 2024, he signed a new long-term contract with Liverpool.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cwylgj7ynljo |title=Quansah signs long-term Liverpool deal |website=BBC Sport |date=7 October 2024 |access-date=8 October 2024}}</ref>

On 27 April 2025, Liverpool won the [[2024–25 Premier League]], after a 5–1 win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] earning Quansah his second trophy at the club.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cj3x2ee1261t|title=Liverpool 5–1 Tottenham Hotspur|first=Phil|last=McNulty|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 April 2025|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref>

===Bayer Leverkusen===
On 2 July 2025, Quansah signed for [[Bundesliga]] side [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] on a five-year deal for an initial fee of £30 million, with an additional £5 million in add-ons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bayer04.de/de-de/news/bayer04/u21-europameister-jarell-quansah-wechselt-aus-liverpool-zu-bayer-04 |title=U21-Europameister Jarell Quansah wechselt aus Liverpool zu Bayer 04 |publisher=Bayer 04 Leverkusen |language=German |date=2 July 2025 |access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/jarell-quansah-completes-transfer-bayer-leverkusen |title=Jarell Quansah completes transfer to Bayer Leverkusen |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |date=2 July 2025 |access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13391330/jarell-quansah-transfer-news-defender-completes-move-from-liverpool-to-bayer-leverkusen |title=Jarell Quansah transfer news: Defender completes move from Liverpool to Bayer Leverkusen |website=Sky Sports |date=2 July 2025 |access-date=2 July 2025}}</ref> On 23 August, he scored his first goal on his Bundesliga debut in a 2–1 home defeat against [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim|Hoffenheim]], By scoring his first goal for Leverkusen, he did his former Liverpool teammate [[Diogo Jota]]’s gaming celebration as a tribute to him.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/jarrel-quansah-nets-debut-goal-but-bayer-leverkusen-fall-to-hoffenheim-in-bundesliga-opener |title=Jarrel Quansah nets debut goal but Bayer Leverkusen fall to Hoffenheim in Bundesliga opener |publisher=GhanaSoccernet |date=23 August 2025 }}</ref>

== International career ==
Eligible to play for England as well as Scotland, Ghana, and Barbados through his grandparents,<ref name=":1"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2022/03/liverpool-youngster-rejects-attempt-to-switch-nationality-its-too-complicated/|website=This is Anfield|accessdate=6 August 2022|title=Liverpool youngster rejects attempt to switch nationality|first=Jack|last=Lusby|date=22 March 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=El Akyereko |date=3 September 2019 |title=Liverpool's Jarell Quansah On The Attitude To Succeed And Talks Up The Determination To Reach Virgil Van Dijk's Heights |url=https://sportsworldghana.com/liverpools-jarell-quansah-on-the-attitude-to-succeed-and-talks-up-the-determination-to-reach-virgil-van-dijks-heights/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=SportsWorldGhana |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Lusby |first=Jack |date=29 June 2022 |title=Who is Jarell Quansah? The 19-year-old shining for England |url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2022/06/who-is-jarell-quansah-the-19-year-old-liverpool-defender-shining-for-england/ |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=This Is Anfield |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=21 March 2021 |title=Ghana targets Jarell Quansah and Kwadwo Baah named in England U18 squad |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-targets-jarell-quansah-and-kwadwo-baah-named-in-england-u18-squad |access-date=30 June 2022 |website=GhanaSoccernet |language=en}}</ref> Jarell Quansah first played with England youth teams, from [[England national under-16 football team|under-16s]] level to the [[England national under-19 football team|under-19s]].<ref name=":2"/><ref name=":3"/>

In June 2022, Quansah was included in the England squad for the [[2022 UEFA European Under-19 Championship|2022 Under-19 Euros]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Frank Smith |date=17 June 2022 |title=England MU19s squad named for EUROs |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Jun/17/england-mu19s-squad-named-for-UEFA-U19-EURO-in-Slovakia-20221706  |access-date=28 June 2022 |website=[[The Football Association]] |language=en}}</ref> Starting all games as a centre-back during the competition in [[Slovakia]], he played a key role in England's successful campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61980363|title=European Under-19 Championship: Who are the England squad aiming for Euro final success?|first=Alex|last=Howell|date=30 June 2022|accessdate=14 July 2022|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Most notably he scored the winner in the 2–1 semi-final victory against [[Italy national under-19 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Simmonds |first=Kadeem |date=28 June 2022 |title=Liverpool defender Jarell Quansah fires England into Euro Under-19 final |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jarell-quansah-liverpool-england-breaking-24347059 |journal=[[Liverpool Echo]] |language=en |access-date=30 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.si.com/fannation/soccer/futbol/news/jarell-quansah-mimics-steph-curry-in-u19-euros-semi-final|magazine=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=30 June 2022|title=Liverpool's Jarell Quansah Celebrates Like Steph Curry After Firing England To U19 Euros Final|first=Robert|last=Summerscales|date=28 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/live/football/61324529|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 June 2022|title=U19 Euros semi-final – England v Italy|first=Neil|last=Johnston|date=28 June 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/12642651/meet-englands-young-lions-gunning-for-glory-in-under-19s-european-championships-final-against-israel|title=Meet England's Young Lions gunning for glory in Under-19s European Championships final against Israel|first=Zinny|last=Boswell|website=Sky Sports|date=1 July 2022|access-date=10 July 2022}}</ref> On 1 July 2022, Quansah started in the final and provided an assist for [[Callum Doyle]] to score the equaliser as England went on to defeat [[Israel national under-19 football team|Israel]] 3–1 in extra time to win the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under19/news/0277-1585addeb047-8422a993d714-1000--israel-1-3-england-aet-chukwuemeka-and-ramsey-the-extra-time-he/|title=Israel 1–3 England (aet): Chukwuemeka and Ramsey the extra-time heroes as Young Lions fight back|website=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations |first=Sam|last=Honeyman|date=1 July 2022 |access-date=19 November 2022}}</ref><ref name=":8">{{Cite web |last=Turner |first=Matt |date=4 July 2022 |title=The Warrington lads at the heart of England's under 19s Euro win |url=https://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/news/20254542.alfie-devine-jarell-quansah-help-england-win-19-euros/ |access-date=10 July 2022 |website=[[Warrington Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":9">{{Cite web |date=1 July 2022 |title=Jarell Quansah records assist as England U19s seal Euros glory |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/jarell-quansah-records-assist-england-u19s-seal-euros-glory |access-date=10 July 2022 |website=[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool FC]] |language=en}}</ref> His performances during the competition led to his inclusion in the UEFA team of the tournament.<ref name="UEFA">{{Cite web |date=5 July 2022|title=2022 Under-19 EURO Team of the Tournament|url=https://www.uefa.com/news/0277-158d3934d81a-206a691b8c37-1000--u19-euro-team-of-the-tournament/|access-date=14 July 2022|website=[[UEFA]]|language=en}}</ref>

Quansah made his [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] debut during a 2–0 win over [[Germany national under-20 football team|Germany]] in Manchester on 22 March 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Mar/22/england-mu20s-germany-match-report-20232203|website=England Football|accessdate=22 March 2023|title=Report: England MU20s 2–0 Germany|first=Rebecca|last=Lewin|date=22 March 2023}}</ref> On 10 May 2023, Quansah was included in the England squad for the [[2023 FIFA U-20 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/May/11/england-mu20s-squad-named-for-fifa-u20-world-cup-in-argentina-20231005|title=England MU20s squad named for World Cup in Argentina|first=Nick|last=Veevers|date=10 May 2023|accessdate=22 May 2023|website=EnglandFootball.com}}</ref> He started all four of their games at the tournament including the round of sixteen elimination against [[Italy national under-20 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65773042|title=England U20 1-2 Italy U20: Cesare Casadei's late penalty sends Italy through|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 June 2023|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref>

Quansah made his debut for the [[England national under-21 football team|England U21s]] on 12 October 2023, coming on as a substitute in a 9–1 win against [[Serbia national under-21 football team|Serbia U21s]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2023/10/harvey-elliott-nets-brace-as-jarrell-quansah-makes-debut-in-9-goal-thrashing/|website=This is Anfield|accessdate=16 October 2023|title=Harvey Elliott nets brace as Jarrell Quansah makes debut in 9-goal thrashing|first=Adam|last=Beattie|date=13 October 2023}}</ref> A year later he captained England in their last qualifier against [[Azerbaijan national under-21 football team|Azerbaijan]] at [[Ashton Gate (stadium)|Ashton Gate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c4g549knvq8t|title=England U21 7-0 Azerbaijan U21|first=Michael|last=Emons|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 October 2024|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref>

On 21 May 2024, Quansah was announced as a provisional member of the expanded 33-member England squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]], his first call-up to [[England national football team|the senior team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c3gglr8mpzdo|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 May 2024|title=England Euro 2024 squad: Jarell Quansah and Adam Wharton in provisional squad|first1=Alex|last1=Howell|first2=Simon|last2=Stone|date=21 May 2024}}</ref> On 6 June 2024, England manager [[Gareth Southgate]] left Quansah out of the final 26-man squad.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Steinberg |first=Jacob |date=6 June 2024 |title=England's Euro 2024 squad: Grealish and Maguire miss out as final 26 confirmed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jun/06/england-euro-2024-squad-jack-grealish-harry-maguire-final-26 |access-date=6 June 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On 14 March 2025, Quansah was included in [[Thomas Tuchel]]'s first England squad, for [[FIFA World Cup qualification|World Cup qualifying]] matches against [[Albania national football team|Albania]] and [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cwyd6dr6preo|publisher=BBC Sport|title='Surreal feeling' to be named in England squad - Quansah|date=14 March 2025|access-date=14 April 2025}}</ref>

Quansah was included in the England squad for the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cy4key0ydd9o|title=Reds trio named in Carsley's U21 Euros squad|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 June 2025|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref> He played every minute of their tournament<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/jarell-quansah-who-is-premier-league-champion-liverpool-bayer-leverkusen-erik-ten-hag-32747|website=Bundesliga|title=Jarell Quansah: Who is the Premier League champion who swapped Liverpool for Bayer Leverkusen?|date=2 July 2025|access-date=3 July 2025}}</ref> including the [[2025 UEFA European Under-21 Championship final|final]] on 28 June as England defeated [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] 3–2 after extra time to lift the trophy.<ref name="telegraph">{{Cite web |last=Manzi|first=Bobby|title=England's Under-21s overcome Germany in thrilling final to keep Euros crown – latest reaction|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2025/06/28/england-u21-vs-germany-u21-live-score-latest-euros-final/|url-access=subscription|date=28 June 2025|access-date=2 July 2025|website=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name="U21">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cz6g18dz2dpt|title=England U21 3–2 Germany U21 |first=Nick|last=Mashiter|publisher=BBC Sport|date=28 June 2025|access-date=29 June 2025}}</ref>

On 16 November 2025, Quansah made his senior debut for England in a 2–0 away win over [[Albania national football team|Albania]] in  the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Turner |first=Matt |url=https://www.warringtonguardian.co.uk/sport/latest_sport/25625845.jarell-quansah-makes-senior-england-debut-albania/ |title=Jarell Quansah makes senior England debut against Albania |publisher=Warrington Guardian |date=16 November 2025 }}</ref>

On 22 May 2026, Quansah was selected to play in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cd6pwdj0v90t</ref>

== Style of play ==
Quansah is a right-footed [[centre-back]] who also regularly played [[right-back]] during his youth years.<ref name=":2"/><ref name=":0"/> He has been described as a ball-playing defender, able to break the lines with his long passes, while staying calm and focused in defence, and strong and quick-thinking in aerial duels.<ref name=":3"/><ref name=":4"/>

== Personal life ==
Quansah's brother, Keenan, is also a footballer, who plays for [[National League South]] club [[Slough Town F.C.|Slough Town]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisanfield.com/2023/11/12-liverpool-players-whose-brothers-are-also-footballers-including-2-at-the-club/|website=This is Anfield|accessdate=22 November 2023|title=12 Liverpool players whose brothers are also footballers – including 2 at the club! |first=Jack|last=Lusby|date=20 November 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Keenan Quansah Joins the Bulls |url=https://herefordfc.co.uk/2025/06/keenan-quansah-joins-the-bulls/ |website=Hereford F.C. |access-date=3 June 2025 |date=3 June 2025}}</ref>

